@startuml
' M3 hierarchical layout showcase: a layered architecture with nested
' clusters and cross-cluster edges. Highlights the new behaviour:
'
' • Nested clusters: `Application > API > Controller` and
'   `Application > Service > {UserService, OrderService}`. The
'   3-level tighten pass keeps each nested bbox strictly inside its
'   parent.
'
' • Cross-cluster ranking inside `Application`: the
'   `Controller --> UserService` / `--> OrderService` edges force
'   `API` to rank above `Service` even though declaration order is
'   the reverse-friendly default.
'
' • Top-level cluster ranking: `Service --> Infrastructure` (via
'   `UserService --> Database` etc.) ranks `Application` above
'   `Infrastructure`, instead of letting both sit side-by-side.
'
' Pre-M3 the cross-cluster edges were dropped from the super-graph;
' you'd see `Application` and `Infrastructure` next to each other and
' the API → Service block in declaration order. With M3 every edge
' is a real ranking constraint.

package "Application" {
  package "API" {
    class Controller {
      + handle(req)
    }
  }
  package "Service" {
    class UserService {
      + findUser(id)
    }
    class OrderService {
      + placeOrder()
    }
  }
}

package "Infrastructure" {
  class Database
  class Cache
}

Controller --> UserService
Controller --> OrderService
UserService --> Database
OrderService --> Database
OrderService --> Cache
@enduml
